Introduction¶

In today's digital age, data has become an integral part of our lives. Every time we browse the internet, make a purchase, or use a social media platform, we generate enormous amounts of data. This data contains valuable insights that can help businesses make informed decisions and improve their operations. However, analyzing this data can be a daunting task, especially when dealing with vast amounts of unstructured data.

Businesses face various challenges in analyzing data, such as identifying patterns and trends, making predictions, and extracting insights. Traditional methods of data analysis, such as manual data entry and basic statistical analysis, are time-consuming and often insufficient in dealing with large datasets. Additionally, the sheer volume of data generated every day makes it nearly impossible for humans to process and analyze it all.

This is where machine learning comes in. By leveraging advanced algorithms, machine learning can help businesses analyze large datasets quickly and efficiently. Machine learning algorithms can identify patterns and relationships in data, make predictions, and learn from past experiences to improve their performance over time. This makes it a powerful tool for businesses looking to gain insights and make data-driven decisions.

With the increasing availability of data and the rapid advancements in machine learning technology, businesses that fail to leverage this powerful tool risk falling behind their competitors. Therefore, it is crucial for businesses to embrace machine learning and invest in the development of machine learning models to stay ahead in today's data-driven world.

What is Machine Learning¶

Machine learning is a sub-field of computer science that involves the development of algorithms that enable computers to learn from data without being explicitly programmed. In other words, machine learning allows computers to improve their performance over time by learning from experience.

At its core, machine learning is a research field that sits at the intersection of statistics, artificial intelligence, and computer science. It has its roots in the study of pattern recognition and computational learning theory, and has since grown to encompass a wide range of applications in areas such as natural language processing, computer vision, and robotics.

Machine learning algorithms can be broadly classified into two types: supervised and unsupervised learning. Supervised learning involves training a machine learning model on labeled data, where the correct output is already known. Unsupervised learning, on the other hand, involves training a model on unlabeled data, where the correct output is unknown.

The application of machine learning methods has become increasingly ubiquitous in everyday life. From automatic movie recommendations, to suggestions of food and products based on our shopping history, to personalized music streaming services and recognizing our friends in digital photos, many modern apps and services have machine learning algorithms at their core. When we look at a complex website like Facebook, Amazon, or Netflix, it is very likely that every part of their service contains multiple machine learning models.

Traditional Programming vs Machine Learning

Why Machine Learning?¶

In the early days of "intelligent" applications, many systems used handcoded rules of "if" and "else" decisions to process data or adjust to user input.

Think of a spam filter whose job is to move the appropriate incoming email messages to either the inbox or a spam folder. We could make up a blacklist of words that would result in an email being marked as spam. This would be an example of using an expert-designed rule system to design an "intelligent" application. Manually crafting decision rules is feasible for some applications, particularly those in which humans have a good understanding of the process to model.

However, using handcoded rules to make decisions has two major disadvantages:

  • The logic required to make a decision is specific to a single domain and task. Changing the task even slightly might require a rewrite of the whole system.
  • Designing rules requires a deep understanding of how a decision should be made

by a human expert.

Another Example

One example of where this handcoded approach will fail is in detecting faces in images. Today, every smartphone can detect a face in an image. However, face detection was an unsolved problem until as recently as 2001. The main problem is that the way in which pixels (which make up an image in a computer) are "perceived" by the computer is very different from how humans perceive a face. This difference in representation makes it basically impossible for a human to come up with a good set of rules to describe what constitutes a face in a digital image.

But, using machine learning, however, simply presenting a program with a large collection of images of faces is enough for an algorithm to determine what characteristics are needed to identify a face.

Features/Predictor¶

Predictor variables, also known as feature variables, are the input variables used in a machine learning model to make predictions about the target variable. These variables are typically represented as columns in a dataset, and can take on different types of data, including numerical data (such as the number of bedrooms in a house), categorical data (such as the zip code of a house), or text data (such as a description of a product).

In the context of predicting house prices, some examples of predictor variables could be the number of bedrooms, the area in square meters, the number of floors, and the zip code of a house. These variables are used by the machine learning model to try to identify patterns and relationships that exist between them and the target variable, which is the variable we want to predict.

Target variables¶

The target variable, also known as the response variable or dependent variable, is the variable that we want to predict using the predictor variables. In the case of predicting house prices, the target variable could be the actual price of a house, or a categorical variable indicating the price range of a house (such as high, medium, or low).

In the machine learning model, the target variable is the variable that the model is trying to learn to predict based on the input provided by the predictor variables. The goal of the machine learning model is to find the relationship between the predictor variables and the target variable, so that it can accurately predict the target variable for new, unseen data.

Data Preprocessing¶

Check Missing Values¶

It is important to check for missing values in a dataset before using machine learning algorithms because missing data can have a significant impact on the performance and accuracy of the machine learning models. Missing values can occur in a dataset due to a variety of reasons such as data collection errors, data processing issues, or simply because the data was not collected for certain observations.

Machine learning algorithms typically require complete datasets to be able to learn and make accurate predictions. If there are missing values in the dataset, the algorithm may not be able to make accurate predictions or may result in biased results.

In addition, some machine learning algorithms do not handle missing values well and may either fail or introduce additional bias into the model. Therefore, it is important to handle missing values appropriately before applying machine learning algorithms. This can include imputing missing values using various techniques such as mean imputation, median imputation, or using machine learning models to predict missing values.

Overall, checking for and handling missing values is a critical step in the data preprocessing stage before applying machine learning algorithms.

  1. Delete rows with missing values

  3. Use the ML model to find the missing values, for example, MICE (Multiple Imputation by Chained Equation) or KNN Imputation.

Check Duplicates Values¶

It is important to check for duplicate data before using machine learning because duplicates can affect the accuracy of the machine learning model. When there are duplicate records in the dataset, it can result in a biased model as the model may give more importance to these duplicate records. This can result in overfitting, which means that the model is too complex and has learned the noise in the data instead of the underlying pattern.

Furthermore, duplicate data can lead to inaccurate results when performing statistical analysis on the dataset. This is because the duplicate data inflates the sample size and therefore, the statistical analysis may overestimate the true significance of the results.

Therefore, it is important to identify and remove duplicate data before training the machine learning model. This can be done by checking for duplicate rows or duplicate columns in the dataset. If duplicate data is found, it can either be removed or merged with the original data, depending on the context of the problem and the nature of the duplicates.

In [ ]:

Out[ ]:

The dataset is clean enough. If our dataset in another project has duplicated values, handling duplicate values can depend on the context in which they occur, but here are several general ways to handle them:

  1. Remove duplicates: One way to handle duplicates is to remove them altogether. This can be useful if we only need the unique values in a data set or if duplicates are causing issues in a program.
  2. Keep only one copy of duplicates: Another approach is to keep only one copy of each duplicate value. This can be useful if we want to preserve some information from the duplicates, such as the first or last occurrence.

Handle Numerical Data: Outliers¶

Handling outliers in numerical data is an important step in machine learning, as these extreme values can significantly affect the performance of a model. Outliers are data points that lie far away from the majority of the data points and may arise due to measurement errors, data entry errors, or other anomalies. These outliers can skew the distribution of the data and cause issues in modeling, such as overfitting.

There are several techniques to handle outliers in numerical data. One approach is to remove the outliers altogether, but this can result in a loss of important information and may not be feasible if the dataset is small. Another approach is to treat the outliers as missing values and impute them with a suitable value. This can be done by replacing the outliers with the median or mean of the data or just keeping it to gain rich information about the data.

By using statistical methods such as z-score or interquartile range (IQR) to detect and handle the outliers. The z-score method identifies outliers based on their distance from the mean while IQR method identifies outliers based on their distance from the first and third quartiles. These methods can help identify and handle outliers more accurately.

Let's check our numerical variable using boxplot:

In [ ]:
employees.boxplot(column=num_features);

Insight: There are no outlier in our data.

If our dataset in another project has outlier value, here are several ways to handle outliers in Python:

Remember, the choice of approach depends on your specific goals and the nature of your data. By considering these different methods, you can decide how to handle outliers while prioritizing the retention of their valuable information for your model.

  1. Correct Value: Correcting a data point to its proper value. Let's say you have a dataset that records the heights of individuals. The data is supposed to be in meters, but there was an error during data entry, and someone mistakenly input the values in centimeters. For instance, the height of a person is recorded as 170, which should be interpreted as 170 centimeters instead of the intended 170 meters. To correct this error and convert the height to the proper value in meters, you need to divide the recorded value by 100. In this case, the corrected height would be 1.70 meters.

  2. Remove Outliers: One way to handle outliers is by selectively removing extreme values from the dataset. However, this method may result in a loss of data and potentially biased results.

  3. Replacing with Statistical Measures: Instead of removing outliers, you can replace them with more representative values derived from statistical measures. Calculate the median or other robust statistical measures that are less sensitive to outliers, and use them as replacements for outliers while retaining the rest of the dataset unchanged. This method make them less extreme and this technique suitable for small datasets with numerous outliers that negatively impact the model's performance. But, care should be taken to consider the implications of modifying the original data!!!

  4. Keeping Outliers as They Are: If you want to preserve the outliers without modifying them, you can simply do nothing. Leave the outliers as they are in the dataset, and include them in your analysis without any alterations. This approach acknowledges the rich information contained in outliers and allows your model to learn from their unique patterns.

Overall, by choosing to keep outliers as they are, you will more prioritize gaining rich information that can enhance your business insights and provide a more accurate representation of the underlying data distribution.

Reference:

  • Best-Practice Recommendations for Defining, Identifying, and Handling Outliers
  • How to Detect and Handle Outliers

The above plot is referred to as a box plot, also known as a box-and-whisker plot, is a graphical representation of the distribution of a dataset. The box plot depicts the five-number summary as follows:

  • Q1: the first quartile (25th percentile of the data)
  • Median: the second quartile (50th percentile of the data)
  • Q3: the third quartile (75th percentile of the data)
  • Lower whisker: the lower fence
  • Upper whisker: the upper fence
  • Data outside the fences are considered outliers.

Warning, The lower whisker is not the minimum value of the data, and the upper whisker is not the maximum value of the data.

When a box plot includes outliers, they are typically represented as individual points that are plotted outside of the whiskers. Outliers are important to identify because they may represent extreme or unusual values that can have a significant impact on the interpretation of the data.

To identify outliers, there are some methods, such as

  • IQR method: This method involves identifying the interquartile range (IQR) of the data and removing any values outside of a specified range. The IQR is defined as the difference between the third quartile (75th percentile) and the first quartile (25th percentile). Any value that is more than 1.5 times the IQR away from the quartiles is considered an outlier.

  • Z-score method: This method involves calculating the z-score of each data point, which measures how many standard deviations away from the mean the data point is. Any data point with a z-score greater than a specified threshold (e.g., 3) is considered an outlier. We can use the zscore function from the scipy.stats module to calculate the z-scores

In [ ]:
# this code can be your reference if want check which one is outlier
Q1 = employees[num_features].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = employees[num_features].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
outlier_mask = ((employees[num_features] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (employees[num_features] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)))
total_rows_with_outliers = len(employees[outlier_mask.sum(axis=1) > 0])

print("Total rows with outliers: ", total_rows_with_outliers, "rows or around ", 
      round(total_rows_with_outliers/employees.shape[0], 2), "%")

Total rows with outliers:  0 rows or around  0.0 %

Insight: Given that our dataset is large and the percentage of outliers is 0%, we decided to keep the dataset as they are.

Handle Categorical Data: Encoding¶

Categorical data refers to data that is divided into groups or categories, where each observation belongs to a particular category. In machine learning, categorical data is an essential part of many datasets and can provide valuable insights into the behavior of a system or the characteristics of a group.

Categorical data can be further divided into two types: nominal and ordinal. Nominal data refers to data that is not ordered or ranked, such as gender or eye color. On the other hand, ordinal data refers to data that is ordered or ranked, such as education level or income bracket.

Handling categorical data in machine learning is essential as most machine learning algorithms require numerical input data. There are several ways to handle categorical data in machine learning, including one-hot encoding, label encoding, and target encoding.

  • One-hot encoding is a process of representing categorical data as binary vectors, where each category is represented by a binary digit (0 or 1) in a vector. For example, if we have a categorical feature "color" with three possible values - red, green, and blue, one hot encoding would represent these values as [1,0,0], [0,1,0], and [0,0,1] respectively. One hot encoding is useful for algorithms that cannot handle categorical data directly, such as linear regression or support vector machines.

  • Label encoding is another method of encoding categorical data where each category is assigned a unique numerical value. For example, if we have a categorical feature "color" with three possible values - red, green, and blue, label encoding would represent these values as 1, 2, and 3, respectively. However, label encoding assumes an ordinal relationship between the categories, meaning that the numerical values assigned to each category imply an order or ranking. This can lead to issues if the categories do not have a natural order, such as with the colors red, green, and blue.

  • Ordinal encoding is similar to label encoding, but instead of assigning arbitrary numerical values to the categories, the values are assigned based on their rank or order. For example, if we have a categorical feature "size" with three possible values - small, medium, and large, ordinal encoding would represent these values as 1, 2, and 3, respectively. Unlike label encoding, ordinal encoding is appropriate when there is a natural order to the categories.

In summary, handling categorical data in machine learning is important because many algorithms cannot handle categorical data directly. One hot encoding is a method that represents categorical data as binary vectors, while label encoding and ordinal encoding are methods that assign numerical values to each category. Label encoding assumes an ordinal relationship between the categories, while ordinal encoding assigns values based on their rank or order. By handling categorical data correctly, machine learning algorithms can use this information effectively to make accurate predictions or classifications.

One-Hot Encoding¶

One of the ways to do one-hot encoding in Python is by using the pd.get_dummies() method from the Pandas library.

pd.get_dummies() takes a DataFrame or Series containing categorical data as input and returns a new DataFrame with the categorical variables replaced by binary (0/1) columns representing the presence or absence of a particular category.

For example, suppose we have a dataset with a categorical variable color that can take on the values 'red', 'green', and 'blue'. We can apply one-hot encoding to this variable using pd.get_dummies() as follows:

{python}
data = {'color': ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'red', 'green']}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)

encoded_df = pd.get_dummies(df['color'])

The resulting encoded_df DataFrame will have three columns, one for each category in the color variable:

{python}
   blue  green  red
0     0      0    1
1     0      1    0
2     1      0    0
3     0      0    1
4     0      1    0

Each row in the new DataFrame represents a single observation from the original dataset, with 1s indicating the presence of a particular category and 0s indicating its absence.

One-hot encoding is particularly useful when dealing with nominal categorical data, where there is no inherent ordering between categories.

Label Encoding¶

Label Encoding is a technique to convert categorical variables into numerical variables. In pandas, we can use the cat.codes attribute to perform Label Encoding. This attribute assigns a unique integer to each unique value in a categorical variable. To use cat.codes, we need to first convert the categorical variable to a pandas Categorical data type using the astype method. Once we have done this, we can then use the cat.codes attribute to perform the label encoding.

But, the label encoding assigns numerical labels to categories based on an arbitrary order. In the case of the City column. This numerical representation may inadvertently introduce a misleading sense of order or hierarchy among the categories. For example, if we label categories as 0, 1, and 2, the model might incorrectly assume that category 2 is greater than category 1, which can lead to incorrect interpretations or biased predictions. Or the model may incorrectly infer relationships or patterns that don't actually exist.

While one-hot encoding increases dimensionality, it provides a more accurate representation of categorical variables and allows models to capture the unique characteristics of each category. One-hot encoding avoids these issues by creating separate binary columns for each category, treating them independently and preserving the categorical nature of the data. It also ensures equal importance and avoids distorting distances or relationships between categories.

Train-Test Splitting¶

Before we start building a machine learning model, it's important to split our data into training and testing sets. This process is known as train-test splitting. The purpose of train-test splitting is to evaluate the performance of our model on unseen data.

Train-test splitting is a crucial step in the machine learning process that helps to evaluate the performance of a model on unseen data. It is typically used when we have a dataset and want to build a machine learning model to make predictions or classify new observations. In general, we need to perform train-test splitting whenever we want to estimate how well a machine learning model will perform on new data. This can occur in a variety of situations, such as developing a predictive model for customer churn, building a recommendation system, or classifying data.

Without train-test splitting, we may develop a model that performs well on the training data but fails to generalize to new, unseen data. This is known as overfitting and can result in poor model performance. Therefore, it's important to split the data into training and testing sets to evaluate the model's performance on new data. Additionally, train-test splitting can help us to choose the best machine learning algorithm or hyperparameters for a given problem. By evaluating the performance of different models on the testing set, we can select the one that performs the best on unseen data.

To perform train-test splitting, we randomly divide the dataset into two sets - a training set and a testing set. The training set is used to train the model, while the testing set is used to evaluate the model's performance. The testing set should be representative of the overall data and should not be used in any way during the training process to prevent overfitting.

Before we can do train-test splitting, we need to separate our dataset into two parts, the target variable (y) and the predictor variable (X).

  • y : Stores the target column of the dataset
  • X : Stores the predictor columns, which is all the columns except the target column and the unique identifier column.
In [ ]:
y = employees['Status_Left']
X = employees.drop(['Status_Left', 'EmployeeId'], axis=1)

The EmployeeId column is a unique identifier, therefore it doesn't hold relevant information about employee characteristics that would help the model to learn.

We can split the dataset using the train_test_split() function, therefore we are going to import it first.

In [ ]:
# import train_test_split function from sklearn.model_selection module
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

We can use train_test_split with the following parameters.

  • *arrays: dataframes that we use (separated, for predictors and target variables)
  • test_size: the percentage of data to be used as test data.
  • train_size: the percentage of data to be used as test data (will be filled automatically if test_size is assigned a value)
  • random_state: random number generator (RNG) value. If we enter an integer value for this parameter, it will produce the same result for the same value. If we change the value, then the result will be different.

NOTES: The most common method of train-test splitting involves using 80% of the data for training and the remaining 20% for testing. However, the split ratio can vary depending on the size of the dataset and the specific problem at hand.

In [ ]:
# split dataset into training set and test set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,
                                                    y,
                                                    test_size = 0.2, # 80% training and 20% test
                                                    random_state = 42)

After splitting the data, we train the machine learning model on the training set and evaluate its performance on the testing set. This allows us to estimate how well the model will generalize to new, unseen data. If the model performs well on the testing set, we can be confident that it will perform well on new data.

Standardization¶

After splitting our dataset into training and testing sets, we may need to standardize our data to ensure that the features are on the same scale. Standardization is a common preprocessing step in machine learning that aims to scale the features of a dataset to have zero mean and unit variance. This is achieved by subtracting the mean of each feature from each data point and dividing it by the standard deviation of the feature.

One way to perform standardization in Python is by using the StandardScaler class from the sklearn.preprocessing module. This class provides a convenient way to standardize our data by fitting a scaler object on the training data and transforming both the training and testing data using the fitted scaler.

Standardizing the data is important because many machine learning algorithms use some form of distance measure to learn patterns, and features on different scales can affect the performance of the model. For instance, features with larger values can dominate the distance measure and have a greater impact on the model, leading to biased or inaccurate results.

Standardization helps to overcome this problem by scaling the features to a standard range, which allows for accurate learning of patterns and improves the performance of the model. In addition, standardization can also help to speed up the convergence of some machine learning algorithms, such as gradient descent, by making the cost function smoother and reducing the number of iterations needed to reach convergence.

Additional: Standardization vs Normalization

In general, normalization is used when the features of the dataset have a Gaussian distribution, and standardization is used when the features do not have a Gaussian distribution.

  • Normalization involves scaling the features of a dataset to a specific range, typically between 0 and 1. It is commonly used when the features of the dataset have a Gaussian distribution (bell curve) or when the features have different units of measurement (e.g., height in inches and weight in pounds).

    Normalized Value = (X - X_min) / (X_max - X_min)

    Description:

    • X is the original value you want to normalize.
    • X_min is the minimum value of the feature in the dataset.
    • X_max is the maximum value of the feature in the dataset.

  • Standardization involves scaling the features of a dataset to have a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one. It is typically used when the features of the dataset do not follow a Gaussian distribution. Standardization is performed by subtracting the mean of the feature from each data point and then dividing the result by the standard deviation of the feature.

    Standardized Value (Z) = (X - Mean) / Standard Deviation

    Description:

    • X is the original value you want to standardize.
    • Mean is the mean (average) value of the variable.
    • Standard Deviation is the standard deviation of the variable.

Model Building: Support Vector Machine (SVM)¶

SVM in Classification: Support Vector Classifier (SVC)¶

To fit a model to our need, we'll need an algorithm. There are many types of machine learning algorithms and one such example is the Support Vector Machine. Support Vector Machine (SVM) is a family of extremely powerful models that can be used in classification and regression problems. These are highly favored by many people because they are able to produce significant accuracy without requiring considerable computational power.

SVM can solve classification ("Support Vector Classifier") and regression ("Support Vector Regressor") problems and can be extended to model non-linearity in the data.

SVC aims at finding decision boundaries that separate observations with differing class memberships. In other words, SVC is a discriminative classifier formally defined by a separating hyperplane. Let us start with a simple example. Suppose that for a given dataset, we have to classify black tringle from red circles as shown in the image below.

As we attempt to separate these classes through a hyperplane in multidimensional space, there can be many candidate lines that achieve this task, as illustrated below. The black line, blue line, and green line are perfectly viable candidates.

Which of the 3 lines better differentiate the data into two classes?

  1. Here, the black line is closer to black tringles as compare to blue circles.
  2. The green line seems to differentiate the two classes better. However, we have yet to formally establish the green line as the universal line -- in the following section we will see how to do this.

Key Points¶

The basic idea of SVC: maximize the distance (margin) between the hyperplane and the nearest sample point. The best line is the line that, as much as possible, provides a maximally large margin between the two classes.

This is illustrated in the following figure:

  • Optimal hyper-plane: A hyperplane in two dimensions is simply a line that best separates the data. This line is like the decision boundary between the classes, as shown in the image above. In the case of three-dimensional data distribution, the hyperplane would be a two-dimensional surface and not a line.

  • Support Vector: The closest points from both the classes to the hyperplane are called support vectors. Using the support vectors, the algorithm maximizes the margin between classes. By any means, if the support vectors are changed, the position of the hyperplane will also change.

  • Margin: The distance between the support vectors and the hyperplane is called a margin.

Additional: Math intuition behind SVM¶

In a two-dimension space we can visualize this as a line and let’s assume that all of our input points can be completely separated by one line. The equation of the separating hyperplane is as follow:

$w⋅x−b=0$

Where the coefficients ($w$) that determine the slope of the line and the intercept ($b$) are found by the learning algorithm, and x1 and x2 are the two input variables. That equation is from basic linear equation ($y = mx + c= 0$). Given a data point $w$, if $w⋅x$ is evaluated to to be bigger than $b$, it belongs to a corresponding class. If it is evaluated to be less than $b$, then it belongs to another class.

  • A value close to the line returns a value close to zero and the point may be difficult to classify.

$$Accuracy = {\text{Number of correct predictions} \over \text{Total number of predictions}}.$$

Reguralization (C)¶

By default, Support Vector Machine implements Hard Margin SVM. It works well only if our data is linearly separable. Hard Margin SVM does not allow any misclassification to happen. It tries to find the best hyperplane that can separate the data.

In case our data is non-separable/ nonlinear then the Hard Margin SVM will not return any hyperplane as it will not be able to separate the data. This is where Soft Margin SVM comes into the picture.

Soft margin SVM allows some misclassification to happen by relaxing the hard constraints of Support Vector Machine. Soft margin SVM is implemented with the help of the Regularization parameter (C).

Regularization parameter (C): It tells us how much misclassification we want to avoid.

  • Hard margin SVM generally has large values of C.
  • Soft margin SVM generally has small values of C.

Now that we know what the Regularization parameter (C) does, we need to understand its relation with Support Vector Machine.

Relation between Regularization parameter (C) and SVM

  • As the value of C increases the margin decreases (Hard SVM).
  • If the values of C are very small the margin increases (Soft SVM).

To simplify, when C is large the SVM tends to be overfitting, while when C is small the SVM tends to be underfitting.

Gamma¶

The Gamma values used in SVM are similar to the C values. Gamma is a parameter for non-linear hyperplanes. The gamma parameter defines how far the influence of a single training example reaches, with low values meaning 'far' and high values meaning 'close'. The gamma parameters can be seen as the inverse of the radius of influence of samples selected by the model as support vectors.

  • Large Gamma: The decision boundary will be influenced by fewer data points. As a result, overfitting results from the decision boundary being non-linear.

  • Small Gamma: The decision boundary will be influenced by more data points. The decision boundary is hence more generic.

Insight: After Use Standarized Features (X_train_ss)¶

It looks like you've used a support vector machine (SVM) classifier and observed changes in accuracy after applying standard scaling to the features. Let's break down the insights:

Initial Accuracy:

  • Training Accuracy: 65.63%

  • Testing Accuracy: 65.52%

After Standard Scaling:

  • Training Accuracy: Improved to 78.13%

  • Testing Accuracy: Improved to 79.16%

Result:

  • Scaling Impact: The increase in accuracy after applying standard scaling suggests that the SVM model benefits from having features on a similar scale. SVMs are sensitive to the scale of input features, so standardizing them (scaling to mean = 0 and standard deviation = 1) often improves model performance. When features are on different scales, the SVM might give more importance to features with larger scales. Standard scaling ensures that all features contribute equally.

  • Overfitting/Underfitting: The fact that the testing accuracy improved suggests that scaling helped in generalization. It's important to check for overfitting or underfitting; a significant gap between training and testing accuracy might indicate overfitting, while low accuracies on both may indicate underfitting.

SVM In Regression: Support Vector Regressor¶

Support Vector Machines (SVMs) are well known in classification problems. So, can svm be used for predict discrete values or regression?

The answer is yes -- by using the same principle of SVMs, we can use SVMs for regression problems. The only difference is that instead of using the hyperplane to separate the classes, we use the hyperplane to predict the value of the target variable, a method that goes by the name of Support Vector Regression (SVR).

Why SVR?

How does SVR compares to simple regression? In simple regression, we aim to reduce the error rate. While using SVR, we attempt to keep the error within predetermined limits.

SVR has the following advantages,

  • SVR performs lower processing compared to other regression techniques.
  • Has excellent generalization ability, with high prediction accuracy.

Outliers may represent genuine and meaningful data points that carry important information about the underlying distribution of the data. Removing or replacing these outliers may result in a biased or incomplete analysis of the data.

Instead, it may be more appropriate to leave the outliers as they are and adjust the analysis or model accordingly. For instance, we may consider using robust statistical methods that are less sensitive to outliers or implementing a separate analysis that focuses specifically on the outliers. It may also be useful to explore the reasons behind the presence of outliers and determine if they are the result of measurement error, data entry error, or other factors that may be addressed directly.

Standardization¶

StandardScaler is a preprocessing technique in machine learning that is used to standardize the scale of numeric features in a dataset. It transforms the data so that it has a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.

The purpose of standard scaling is to bring all the features to a similar scale, which can be important for certain machine learning algorithms.

It has two important methods:

  • fit(X): This method takes the input data X, which is a two-dimensional array-like object or a pandas dataframe, and computes the mean and standard deviation of each feature in the data. These statistics are used to standardize the data in the transform() method.

  • transform(X): This method takes the input data X and standardizes the scale of each feature in the data using the mean and standard deviation computed by the fit() method. The standardized data is then returned as a new array-like object.

Model Evaluation: Mean Absolute Error (MAE)¶

To find out how good our model is, we can calculate the prediction error (error) with the evaluation metric. One of the most popular regression models is Mean Absolute Error (MAE). With MAE, we calculate the average error of all predictions, after taking the absolute value of the error. This prevents the error from canceling out each out when we add them up.

Here is the mathematical function of the Mean Absolute Error:

$$MAE = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left | y_{pred, i} - y_{real, i} \right |}{n}$$

To compute the Mean Absolute Error, we can import scikit-learn's mean_absolute_error function.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error
In [ ]:
print("SVR Model (MAE)")
print("  Train:", mean_absolute_error(svr_model.predict(X_train), y_train))
print("  Test:", mean_absolute_error(svr_model.predict(X_test), y_test))

Model Improvement: Tuning Hyperparameters SVR¶

Let's now dive into the hyperparameters that can affect the model performance of our Support Vector Regressor.

Reguralization (C)¶

Reguralization (C) in SVR affects how our algorithm minimizes the error. The algorithm respond to an increase in C by capturing more points inside the epsilon-tube. Consequently, the algorithm will fit the data better.

While increasing C allows us to fit the data better, it also makes our model less robust, risking overfitting. Hence, it is best to be cautious when tuning hyperparameters and split the data into training and testing datasets so we can evaluate our model with unseen data.

Let's take a look at the effect of choosing two radically different values of C, beginning with 100 and then 0.1.

Tuning kernel='rbf', C=100¶

In [ ]:
svr_model_tuned = svm.SVR(kernel='rbf', C=100)
svr_model_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

create_plot_svr_2_model(diamonds, svr_model, svr_model_tuned)

Insight: It turns out that the results are very good with large C values, where the data fit is better, but care needs to be taken to ensure this does not expose the model to the risk of overfitting

  • When C is large, then SVM will follow more data patterns (meandering), the results for this case are getting better (provided that the case is that the majority of the data is not far from the average data set)
  • When the C is small, it will be straighter/doesn't really follow the data pattern. And if it's too small, the error can be even bigger (C is small, there's a good chance, if our data has a complex pattern, a lot of the data is far from the average)

Kernel¶

Alternative kernels in SVR are actually the same as those in SVM for classification, namely linear, rbf, and polymonial. Then also that basically the best match kernel with this data is rbf.

Insight: The rbf kernel works well in practice and is relatively easy to calibrate (the most flexible), in contrast to other kernels.

Epsilon¶

The epsilon value determines the width of the epsilon-tube around the hyperplane. The points that are in this tube are considered as correct predictions and are not faulted by the algorithm. The epsilon value, in the context of SVR, indicates the scale of the original actual values.

Let's try using a large epsilon (10) and a small epsilon (1)...

Knowledge Check: Machine Learning Workflow - Regression¶

  1. Essentially, the machine learning workflow in the case of regression is almost similar to the case of classification. One of the differences is the evaluation of the model, which utilizes metrics ...

    • A. Mean Absolute Error, which is the ratio of the number of correctly predicted data in absolute terms to the total amount of data.
    • B. Accuracy, which is the ratio of the number of correctly predicted data to the total amount of data.
    • C. Mean Absolute Error, which is the total of all absolute error differences divided by the number of error data.
    • D. Accuracy, which is the total of all absolute error differences divided by the number of error data.

  2. A large C grade will result in ...

    • A. The model fitting the data better but also having a risk of overfitting.
    • B. The model being more tolerant of errors, but if it is too small, it may result in poor model learning (underfitting).

  3. The hyperparameter in SVR, which aims to determine the width of the tolerance space around the estimated function (hyperplane), is

    • A. Regularization (C)
    • B. Kernel
    • C. Gamma
    • D. Epsilon

Conclusion¶

Advantages of SVM¶

  • Even with high dimensional data, support vector machines are very effective.
  • SVM can also work in situations when there are more features in the data set than there are data rows.
  • SVM performs incredibly effectively when classes in the data are well separated by points.
  • SVM can be applied to classification and regression problems.
  • SVM can also be effective when used with image data.

Disadvantages of SVM¶

  • SVM does not work effectively when classes in the data are not well separated from one another, which indicates that there are overlapping classes.
  • The selection of the best kernel for SVM is a challenging undertaking.
  • Comparatively, SVM training on large data sets requires more time.
  • The classification cannot be explained in terms of probability since the SVM, or support vector machine, is not a probabilistic model.

The model selection is a very essential step in dealing with any machine learning task, whether it is a classification or regression problem. Which model being the most appropriate will also depend on a variety of factors (such as the quantity of the training data, the number of features, the distribution of the classes, the types of features, etc.).

Depending on the fitted model, we may then encounter of the following:

  • Overfitting: the model is too closely fitting the facts (low bias and high variance)
  • Underfitting: The dataset is under-fit by the model (high bias and low variance).
  • Optimal-fitting: This model is reliable (bias and variance are balanced).

The ideal situation is scenario 3, where the model is said to neither underfit or overfit.

An undertrained model leads to underfitting, and is said to have high bias. An overtrained model leads to overfitting, and is said to have high variance. An overfitted model may perform well on the training data, but poorly on the test data. The goal is to find a model that generalizes well to unseen data (low bias and low variance).

This bias-variance tradeoff is a fundamental problem of statistical learning theory, and shows up whenever a model is trained with data. A strategy to tackling this tradeoff is to combine multiple models. This is called ensemble learning, and is the topic of the next section. By combining various weak learners, we can produce a robust learner that has low bias and low variance.

Additional: Others Machine Learning Model¶

Creating a model in Python using sklearn is relatively easy and involves a few lines of code. The library offers a consistent API that allows developers to switch between different algorithms with minimal effort. Moreover, sklearn offers a range of preprocessing and evaluation tools that can streamline the entire machine learning pipeline from data preparation to model evaluation.

Some of the popular supervised learning algorithms available in sklearn include linear regression, logistic regression, decision trees, random forests, support vector machines, and neural networks. Each of these algorithms has its strengths and weaknesses and is suitable for different types of problems. For example, linear regression is often used for regression tasks with a continuous target variable, while decision trees are commonly used for classification tasks. Here are some popular supervised learning algorithms in sklearn Python library:

  1. Linear Regression

Linear regression is a popular supervised learning algorithm that is widely used in machine learning. It is a simple algorithm that models the linear relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables.

In Python, linear regression can be easily implemented using the Scikit-Learn library, also known as sklearn. The library provides several classes for implementing linear regression models, including LinearRegression, Lasso, and Ridge.

To implement linear regression in sklearn, we first need to split our data into training and testing sets. We can then create an instance of the LinearRegression class and fit the model to the training data using the fit() method. Once the model is trained, we can use it to make predictions on the testing data using the predict() method.

One of the key advantages of using linear regression is its interpretability. It allows us to easily understand the relationship between the dependent variable and independent variables. For example, in a simple linear regression model with one independent variable, the slope of the line represents the change in the dependent variable for a one-unit change in the independent variable.

Linear regression is widely used in a variety of applications, such as predicting housing prices, stock prices, and sales revenue. However, it is important to note that linear regression assumes a linear relationship between the dependent and independent variables, which may not always be the case in real-world scenarios. Therefore, it is important to evaluate the performance of the model and consider other algorithms if necessary.

  1. Logistic Regression

Logistic regression is a popular classification algorithm that predicts the probability of an input belonging to a particular class. It is a supervised learning algorithm that is widely used in various fields such as finance, healthcare, marketing, and more.

In scikit-learn (sklearn), logistic regression can be implemented using the LogisticRegression class. The model works by fitting a logistic function to the input data, which maps the input features to the predicted probabilities of the output classes. The logistic function used in logistic regression is called the sigmoid function, which takes any real-valued number as input and outputs a probability between 0 and 1.

To use logistic regression in sklearn, we first import the LogisticRegression class from the linear_model module. We can then create an instance of the class and fit the model to our training data using the fit method. Once the model is trained, we can use it to predict the class probabilities of new input data using the predict_proba method or directly predict the class labels using the predict method.

In addition to the basic logistic regression algorithm, sklearn also provides various extensions to logistic regression, such as regularized logistic regression, multi-class logistic regression, and imbalanced classification using weighted logistic regression. These extensions can be helpful in dealing with more complex classification problems.

  1. Naive Bayes

Naive Bayes is a classification algorithm based on Bayes' theorem. The idea behind the algorithm is to calculate the probability of a data point belonging to a certain class given the features of the data point. Naive Bayes assumes that the features are conditionally independent given the class, meaning that the presence of one feature does not affect the presence of another feature. Despite this assumption, Naive Bayes is still a powerful algorithm and often performs well in practice, especially on text classification problems.

Scikit-learn provides several implementations of Naive Bayes, including Gaussian Naive Bayes, Multinomial Naive Bayes, and Bernoulli Naive Bayes. Gaussian Naive Bayes is used for continuous data, while Multinomial and Bernoulli Naive Bayes are used for discrete data, such as text.

To use Naive Bayes in scikit-learn, we first import the appropriate module for the chosen implementation. Then, we create an instance of the classifier and fit it to our training data. After fitting the model, we can make predictions on new data using the predict method. Scikit-learn also provides other methods for evaluating the performance of the model, such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score.

It is important to note that Naive Bayes is a probabilistic algorithm, meaning that it outputs probabilities for each class. These probabilities can be useful in certain applications, such as when we want to know how confident the model is in its prediction. However, in some cases, such as when the model is used for decision-making in critical applications, we may need to threshold these probabilities to make a binary decision.

  1. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)

K-nearest neighbors (KNN) is a simple yet powerful supervised machine learning algorithm used for classification and regression tasks. It is a non-parametric algorithm, which means that it doesn't make any assumptions about the underlying data distribution. Instead, it uses the entire training dataset as a reference to classify new instances based on their similarity to the existing instances.

In KNN, the value of K refers to the number of nearest neighbors that are considered while classifying a new instance. The algorithm finds the K nearest neighbors to the new instance based on some similarity metric, such as Euclidean distance or Manhattan distance, and assigns the new instance to the class that appears most frequently among those K neighbors.

In sklearn, the KNN algorithm is implemented in the KNeighborsClassifier and KNeighborsRegressor classes for classification and regression tasks, respectively. These classes take a number of hyperparameters, such as the value of K, the distance metric to be used, and the weighting function for the neighbors, among others.

It is important to note that KNN can be computationally expensive for large datasets, as the algorithm has to compute the distance between the new instance and all the instances in the training dataset. Therefore, it is often used for small to medium-sized datasets or in situations where the computational cost is not a significant issue.

  1. Decision Tree

Decision tree is a popular machine learning algorithm used for both classification and regression tasks. The algorithm creates a tree-like model of decisions and their possible consequences based on a set of input features. Each internal node of the tree represents a decision based on a particular feature, and each leaf node represents a classification or regression value.

In sklearn, the DecisionTreeClassifier and DecisionTreeRegressor classes are used for classification and regression tasks, respectively. The algorithm works by recursively splitting the data based on the feature that provides the best split, which is determined by maximizing a criterion such as information gain or Gini impurity. The process continues until the tree is fully grown, or until a stopping criterion is met, such as reaching a maximum depth or a minimum number of samples required to split a node.

One advantage of decision trees is their interpretability, as the resulting model can be visualized and easily understood. However, decision trees can also be prone to overfitting, which can be mitigated by tuning hyperparameters such as the maximum depth, minimum number of samples required to split a node, and the criterion used for splitting. Additionally, ensemble methods such as random forests and gradient boosting can be used to improve the performance of decision trees.

  1. Random Forest

Random forest is an ensemble learning method in machine learning that combines multiple decision trees to create a more accurate and stable prediction model. It is a type of bagging algorithm that generates multiple decision trees based on different subsets of the training data and then combines their predictions to generate a final output.

In sklearn, the Random Forest algorithm is implemented in the RandomForestClassifier and RandomForestRegressor classes for classification and regression problems, respectively.

The algorithm works by randomly selecting subsets of the training data and features for each tree in the forest. This helps to reduce overfitting and improve the generalization performance of the model. During training, each tree is built by recursively partitioning the feature space based on the best split criterion that maximizes the information gain or reduction in impurity.

At prediction time, the Random Forest algorithm aggregates the predictions of all the trees to produce a final output. The aggregation can be done by taking the majority vote in classification problems or the average in regression problems.

Random Forest has several advantages over other machine learning algorithms. It can handle both categorical and numerical data, can handle missing values, and is less sensitive to outliers compared to other algorithms like Decision Trees. Additionally, it has the ability to measure feature importance, making it useful for feature selection and understanding the importance of different features in the dataset. However, Random Forest is generally slower and requires more computational resources compared to other algorithms.

  1. Gradient Boosting

Gradient Boosting is a powerful machine learning algorithm for building predictive models. It is a type of ensemble learning, where multiple models are trained and their predictions are combined to create a final prediction. In particular, Gradient Boosting creates a series of decision trees in a specific way to optimize model performance.

In sklearn, Gradient Boosting is implemented in the GradientBoostingClassifier and GradientBoostingRegressor classes. The GradientBoostingRegressor class is used for regression problems, while the GradientBoostingClassifier class is used for classification problems.

Like other ensemble learning methods, Gradient Boosting involves creating multiple models and combining their predictions. However, unlike Random Forests, where each decision tree is trained independently, in Gradient Boosting each decision tree is trained sequentially, with each new tree trying to improve upon the errors of the previous ones. This is done by adjusting the weights of each data point based on the error of the previous prediction.

Gradient Boosting also includes a number of hyperparameters that can be tuned to optimize model performance. These include the learning rate, which controls the contribution of each tree to the final prediction, the number of trees, and the depth of each tree.

In practice, Gradient Boosting is a powerful and flexible algorithm that can be applied to a wide range of problems. It is often used in industry and academia for tasks such as classification, regression, and ranking. However, it can be computationally expensive and requires careful tuning of hyperparameters to avoid overfitting.

  1. XGBoost (Extreme Gradient Boosting)

Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) is a popular machine learning algorithm used for both regression and classification problems. It is an advanced implementation of gradient boosting, which is an ensemble technique that combines multiple weak learners to create a strong learner.

XGBoost is an efficient algorithm that is highly scalable and can handle large datasets with a large number of features. It uses a decision tree-based model and works by iteratively adding new trees to the model to correct the errors of the previous trees.

In XGBoost, each tree is constructed in a way that reduces the loss function of the overall model, which makes it more accurate. Additionally, XGBoost uses a technique called regularization to avoid overfitting by penalizing complex models.

XGBoost is implemented in Python using the XGBoost library, which provides an interface to build, train and evaluate XGBoost models. The library offers a wide range of hyperparameters that can be tuned to optimize the performance of the model. Some of the key hyperparameters include the number of trees, learning rate, maximum depth of trees, and regularization parameters.
